I have ridden the bus for over a year now.  I have made friends in this time, and have gotten to know a few people.  But there is one guy.  Everyone knows of him, but no one knows him.  If you try to speak to him, he stares down his nose at you as if you were an insect.  He sits on the bus everyday, staring straight ahead, talking to no one.  The rest of us joke and laugh, he sits and stares.  For now I will call him "Ed".  

Not too long ago there was some trouble with the bus routes, and we were forced to take a different bus, that drops us off a little further from home.  One of the guys had a ride there, and offered to drop Ed off on his way back through the subdivision.  Ed acted insulted by the offer of help.  All that was offered was a short ride, a little help.  You would think this would be welcomed given the possibility of a two mile walk, but Ed seemed offended by the offer.

We do have good friendships on the bus.  If someone is out for a day, you can expect that everyone of the regulars will ask where they were.  It's like a little family almost, though I doubt any of the friendships will extend past the bus.  Well, maybe the one who is also my neighbor (he lives two doors over from me).
She's cute, she's funny and she's intelligent.  I think I am falling for her.  Now I just have to figure out how to find out how she feels about me.

This was taken from an email sent to me by a friend some time back. His research came from wikipedia. Geek: A person who is fascinated, perhaps obsessively, by technology and imagination.
  • A person who is interested in technology, especially computing and new media. Newest definition, Late 20th and early 21st century.
  • A person with a devotion to something in a way that places him or her outside the mainstream. Late 20th and early 21st century.
  • A derogatory term for one with low social skills, often with average intelligence. It is theorized that many of these people have Asperger's syndrome (a pervasive developmental disorder often referred to as "High Functioning" Autism). Late 20th century.
  • An acronym from the U.S. military. Stands for General Electrical Engineering Knowledge. Unclear whether this was the origin of the newer meanings of geek, or if the acronym was developed because those meanings were already established.
  • A person who swallows live animals, bugs, etc., as a form of entertainment at fairs. Probably originated from the Scottish term 'geck', meaning 'fool'. 19th Century.
  • The most popular Urban Dictionary definition is acute in mirroring the general social acceptance for Geeks: Geek, n. Someone who you beat up in High School and end up working for later in life.
  • Now frequently used in technical fields as an honorific used to describe someone of exceptional knowledge or skill.
Nerd: Traditionally applies to a very intelligent but lonely and socially awkward person, one fascinated by knowledge, especially science and mathematics, and less interested in physical and social activities.
  • In the 1990s, nerds on the internet reclaimed the word as a badge of pride, and began using it as a positive description of any technically competent person.
  • Adopted in the mid-1960s to describe a stereotypical intelligent recluse with poor social skills, often the butt of others' jokes.
  • First appeared in Dr. Seuss' book If I Ran the Zoo, published in 1950, used to describe one of the many comical imaginary animals.
  • Another theory of the word's origin sees it as a version of Mortimer Snerd, the name of a slow-witted character created by ventriloquist Edgar Bergen for his radio show.
  • Yet another theory traces the term to Northern Electric Research and Development, where the employees wore pocket-protectors with the acronym N.E.R.D. on them.
  • And yet another theory claims that the word came from the word "drunk" reversed to "knurd", to describe someone who did not drink at parties.
Relationship between Geek and Nerd:
  • Often disputed by pundits and observers.
  • Some view Geek as a less technically-skilled Nerd.
  • Some maintain that Nerds are technically-skilled and socially-competent, while geeks are technically-skilled and socially-incompetent. Others hold the exact opposite view.
  • Some regional differences in connotation may exist.
  • In the US, West Coast has been noted as considering 'geek' less offensive than 'nerd'. East Coast tends to view 'nerd' as being less offensive, although many dispute this.
  • In Britain, 'geek' is an affectionate term, 'nerd' is an offensive term.
  • Nerd originated in the 1950s as a derogatory term. Geek became widespread during the 1980s and has avoided many of the harsher negative connotations.
  • 'Geek' as a milder form of 'Nerd' may apply to people who are socially insignificant, while 'Nerd' is applied to people who are socially inept.
Also of interest, here is the Unabridged Geek Hierarchy: http://www.brunching.com/images/geekchart.pdf

Friday, and all is well.  No big plans for the weekend, but lots of time to rest.  Job responsibiliities are changing (it's a good thing) and I get to train those who will replace me (that's right, they are replacing me with more than one person) during the next week.  Mostly uneventful as it goes.

My next SCA event for the year - Tournament of Chivalry in Apex, NC.  A nice local event, that I can sit back and enjoy.  It's fast approaching.

I recently had to resign as the baronial chroniclers assistant.  Until I get the issues with my license cleared up, it's just too tough to try and get back and forth.  I hope to be able to offer my assistance again soon, since the chronicler cannot always make the meetings.  

I have been working on redoing *all* the leather on my fighting rig.  Apparently my rig and Pennsic didn't play well together, and I didn't get the rig into dry conditions quick enough.  Once I get it all cleaned up, I can get back to fighting.  I hate that I now have to completely redo the leather spangenhelm I had made to cover my regular helm.  It looked really nice.  

I hope to make my Pennsic reservations soon.

It's Wednesday.  Midweek is setting in, and I already want for Friday.  All in all, a pretty standard week.  A really boring week.  

A quick clearification on my post yesterday...

I am not saying my friend owes me anything.  I was merely saying that the same way I have treated a friend (going out of my way to help out) is the way I would expect a true friend to respond.  A good example is the group of "friends" I had in high school.  When we all left for college, I went out of my way to try and keep in touch.  Email, phone calls, whatever.  But that effort was one sided, emails rarely returned (phone calls even less).  

I guess I fell for the "Hollywood" version of what  a true friend is.  The type of friends you see in movies and on TV.  The friend you can call at 3:00AM, and not have them get upset.  The type of friend I guess I will never know...

So I have been slowing slipping back into depression lately, but I had so far been sucessfully fighting back.  This morning was a huge set back in that arena.  Standing the in the rain for 20 minutes waiting for a bus and realizing that no one, not even those I consider my closest of friends, has my back was a large disappointment to say the least.  I am now at work, slightly damp, and cold.  I have resigned myself to the final and inevitable collapse of the tiny shred of a support structure I once thought I had.  

Maybe it is my misinformed idea of friendship that is the problem.  When a person that I consider one of my best friends started having difficulty due to not having permanent employment, I did what I could to help.  At the time the situation benefitted us both because I am not able to drive right now.  I paid for gas in exchange for rides to work and home (I paid for *much* more gas then was used to transport me).  I also went out of my way to make sure there were groceries in the house, often making trips weekly, so that he could eat (he had become a roommate with us, for some time with out rent being asked).  He is now a full house mate with us, and his rent situation is a dealing with the house owner (we moved into a house in Sept/Oct last year).  After all this, I suddenly find myself in a situation where he often won't answer me.  When I *truly* needed a ride to work this morning due to the driving rain, I knocked on his door to see if it was possible.  No answer.  Not even after knocking six times.  And so I put on a raincoat, and stepped out into the deluge.  I stood in the driving rain for 20 minutes waiting for the bus.  I got to work wet, and cold.  I know that inevitably he will say he did not hear me knocking and I will accept this as reasonable.  But that doesn't explain other things, like leaving the room 5 minutes after I sit down to watch whatever show he is watching.  I don't know what his deal is, and given the myriad of excuses I have heard to this point, I probably never will.  

And so I struggle against the depression alone, no friends to help me.  And for me, this only makes it worse.

I think everyone is happier when I smile and play like the world is ok.  Another day of work ahead, and another night of sleep.  Isn't it fun when you end up in a rut.

I like the look they have in the previews, I hope they keep it looking the same on the screen.   I am (of course) also waiting for Episode 3.  That looks vicious, and I love it.  No happy ending this time.

*takes two more advil*  Oh, well.  I should be able to sit upright long enough by the time the movies open.  

It's been a good week so far, the rest of the week looks good too.

I made it through my first SCA event as major staff.  Not only did the field look good, but I got my Award of Arms, as well.  Not a bad event all in all.  Not only did his Majesty seem impressed by my service, but both the incoming and outgoing baronage had good things to say to him.  It feels good to get an award.  I am now to be known in SCA circles as Lord Anders Knudsen.  I also got word that my Coat of Arms is near approval at corporate, and I should hear back about it soon.  I may be able to soon add "Per fess vert and sable, on a plate an eagle rising sable, wings elevated and displayed" to my SCA signature.  

Feast was amazing.  I left after the fifth course, and they were still bringing food.  I was stuffed.  

Since I have been very busy with changes at work and this event, I have not been posting like I had hoped I would.  Maybe now that things have settled down a bit I can work to correct that.  

It's Valentines Day once again, and I am still looking for a special valentine.  Most of my recent efforts to find a lady for whom to fight at SCA events have fallen short, but I shall continue to try.  Valentine's Day isn't nearly as fun without a valentine.  *sigh*

Well, that's all that is new today.  We shall see what we shall see about tomorrow.

I would be posting a bit more right now, but I am busily writing emails to merchants and persons needing field space for the 30th annual tournament of Ymir (an SCA event).  Between site visits, baronial meetings, planning sessions and email I have been a busy boy.  Just an example, I had 44 emails in one day, just concerning this event (that doesn't count personal and business emails).  I am trying to get myself back into the habit of posting, it keeps my writing skills a little sharper.  If you have any ideas for me to write about for posting, let me know.  It might even help me get back in the posting habit.  

Well, that's the short update for now.  Everyone have fun.

The field was freshly cut, and the sun was shining down. I could smell the hay bales as they baked in the sun. I could see the enemy across the field and they looked more nervous the we did. Most people facing Atlantia look nervous.

Our King stood two rows ahead of me, the local Baron two columns to my right. I knew we would take the lead on the offensive, so I prepared myself. This would be a battle sung about for years to come.

The cannon sounded the beginning of the battle, and we marched forward to meet destiny. Around midfield, the unit to our right engaged, and our King called for us to flank that enemy unit. We plowed into the side of the unit, only to be flanked on our left by another enemy unit. The fighting was fierce and valiant. With the enemy pressing on my left, I turned and joined our Baron in his battles, but the numbers were against us. Another unit had engaged us, and we were being attacked on three sides. I fell along side my Baron, fighting to the last. As I fell, I saw that the army of the east (our ally) was making quick work of the remnants of the units that had engaged us. The battle was won for ourside, but the armies of Atlantia paid the price for that victory. A few minutes later, the cannons signalled the end of the battle. No one from Atlantia had survived.

That was the only battle where the whole of Atlantia fell to the enemy. In every other battle during War week, Atlantia was a major force. To be honest, we were in this battle also, due to the fact that we took a lot of the enemy with us when we died.

The anger was born 
And did convey itself in violence
Sadness died,
And is buried beneath the tree 
In the back yard.
Happiness shone its bright smile 
Across the sky
As a rainbow
All the while my heart did beat.

I haven't been posting too much lately, mainly because I lacked anything to say.  Well, maybe now I should get some info out there.

He made an offer this week, and accepted the counter offer made by the seller. After a little time off, I am back to posting.  Here is a quick post with another of my poems, I hope that all enjoy it.  If you like it, if you hate it, I would appreciate some feedback.  I am ponder sending the book out to see if it would get published, but it is hard to let go of something like this (something so personal) without truthful feedback.  Let me know what you think.

To my broken heart:

I wore my heart upon my sleeve
She struck it without mercy.
I fell down to writhe in pain
She smiled in her glory.

She knows not how she wounds my heart
A secret kept forever
Knowledge of my souls torment
To reach her ears, never.

And so I lament my loss
The love I dare not show
And the pain I feel inside
I hope she shall never know.

Do I dare to speak these words,
Or forever hold my tongue?
A torturous secret to try to keep
From when this had first begun.

I know now that my words did wound
A solitary heart.
I wish I had held my tongue
And not made us to part.

Friendship we did have back then
Closer to be, never.
Dare I reveal my pain?
Dare I speak it ever?

I know the truth inside my soul.
There it should have stayed.
Anything to avoid hurting her
And have my pain delayed.

Some people are intolerant.  They can't handle it when someone doesn't agree with them.  I wish at this point that I was only being vague, but this is a problem that has arisen in the office.  Apparently, I am not allowed to even mention politics or religion at work.  I don't really mention religion anyway, so that's not too big an issue.

What I do find funny, is that the only program that they have on the TV's in the break room is CNN.  So, if you eat lunch at work, and don't go over to the cafeteria, you get 60 mins of political debate and information.  I guess coming back and reporting the news to people is just too political for persons in this office.  I try to report objectively, and just say what happened today, but as with anyone, it sometimes ends up tainted by my views.  

I am not trying to push my politcal agenda on anyone.  I am merely sharing my views.  Some people just can't handle it when you disagree with their views.  Now this has become an issue we have to take up at a team meeting.  Someone has told the manager that this is an issue within the department, and we must now dedicate time to telling people to censor themselves.  

For the sake of office harmony, I will agree to censor myself (even though I have said nothing objectionable).  My requirement in this is to censor the middle school type behaviour and language being used around me.  I have listened to my co-workers use the term "Dusty" to describe a negative connatation on things for over six months.  "That's just Dusty" makes no sense, and I should not have to listen to it 20 times a day.  Some people just need something to complain about I guess.

Today, I have decided to do a technology review to get things started. There are several things that have come to light in the last few days, and while I am only commenting on a couple of them, I suggest that everyone periodicly check Slashdot for updates. Graphics card manufacturer nVidia has now taken a step that I have longed to see. The 6800 series nVidia cards will feature Scan Line Interleaving technology (SLI) and GPU load balancing. For those unfamiliar with this concept the article over at Tom's Hardware does a good job of explaining how the technology works. Sprint PCS has also announced the use of EV-DO technology for broadband enabled phones. I can understand selling wireless broadband for laptops, but why would I need DSL speeds to surf the web on my cellular phone? I barely use the wireless web on it now, and I don't think that speeding up the web access would really bring anything new to the game. One last item of note from yesterdays news: Herman Goldstein, father of the ENIAC and EDVAC computer systems (the first computers) died at the age of 90. I wonder what Mr. Goldstein thought of everything that has come from his work. We have really come a long way since he started us out. That is all for todays technology review.
